{% raw %}<h2>The Problem</h2>

<p>Designers produce visual variations of the same core component. A navigation might need icons, notification badges, status indicators, or popovers alongside its links. Some variations are structural (an accordion nav warrants a new block), but many are visual additions to a component whose <strong>accessibility logic is already correct</strong> &mdash; roving tabindex, ARIA attributes, keyboard navigation, focus management.</p>

<p>React solves this elegantly because components are functions &mdash; you can pass a custom <code>LinkComponent</code>, wrap with a HOC, merge props, split into abstract pieces, or configure via Context so the same component behaves differently in two apps. All of this is natural in a virtual DOM where composition is just function calls.</p>

<p>The question: <strong>what strategies achieve this level of customization in an HTML-first, standards-based framework like Web Everything?</strong></p>


<h2>What Frameworks Do</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Framework</th>
      <th>Configuration Surface</th>
      <th>Content Injection</th>
      <th>Behavioral Composition</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>React</strong></td>
      <td>Props, Context</td>
      <td>children, render props, compound components (Radix, Headless UI)</td>
      <td>Hooks, HOCs</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Vue</strong></td>
      <td>Props, provide/inject</td>
      <td>Scoped slots, renderless components</td>
      <td>Composables (Composition API)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Angular</strong></td>
      <td>Inputs, DI</td>
      <td><code>ng-content</code> with <code>select</code>, <code>ng-template</code></td>
      <td>Directives, services</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Svelte 5</strong></td>
      <td>Props, context</td>
      <td>Snippets (replacing slots)</td>
      <td>Actions, stores</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Lit</strong></td>
      <td>Reactive properties, attributes</td>
      <td>Native <code>&lt;slot&gt;</code></td>
      <td>Decorators, controllers</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Stimulus</strong></td>
      <td><code>data-*-value</code> attributes</td>
      <td>Consumer-owned HTML (headless)</td>
      <td>Multiple controllers on one element</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Shoelace / Web Awesome</strong></td>
      <td>Attributes, CSS custom properties</td>
      <td>Named slots, <code>::part()</code></td>
      <td>Standard custom element lifecycle</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p><strong>Key insight:</strong> Every framework provides three orthogonal mechanisms: <em>how to configure</em> (props/attributes/context), <em>how to inject content</em> (slots/children/projections), and <em>how to compose behavior</em> (hooks/directives/controllers). The question is which web standards map to each.</p>


<h2>Strategy Catalog</h2>

<h3>Strategy A: Behavioral Composition via CustomAttribute</h3>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Details</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td>
      <td>Multiple independent behaviors attach to the same element via HTML attributes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>WE Status</strong></td>
      <td><strong>Already implemented</strong> &mdash; core pattern</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Analogy</strong></td>
      <td>React hooks on a component, Angular directives, Stimulus controllers</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>What it solves</strong></td>
      <td>Adding behaviors (tooltips, keyboard shortcuts, drag handles) to any element without touching it</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Limitation</strong></td>
      <td>Does not inject content &mdash; only adds behavior to existing markup</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Example:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;button on:click="save()" tooltip:show="Save changes" shortcut:key="ctrl+s"&gt;
  Save
&lt;/button&gt;</code></pre>

<p>Three independent behaviors, zero coupling between them. Each manages its own lifecycle and cleanup. This is WE's version of hooks &mdash; except it works on <strong>any element</strong>, not just components you authored.</p>


<h3>Strategy B: Consumer-Owned Markup (Headless Behaviors)</h3>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Details</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td>
      <td>Behaviors discover items via selectors, manage state and ARIA regardless of internal markup</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>WE Status</strong></td>
      <td><strong>Already implemented</strong> &mdash; NavListBehavior, TabGroupBehavior</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Analogy</strong></td>
      <td>Radix Primitives, Downshift props getters, React Aria hooks</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>What it solves</strong></td>
      <td>Consumer controls <em>all</em> markup &mdash; icons, badges, popovers, any HTML &mdash; while behavior manages accessibility</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Limitation</strong></td>
      <td>Consumer must follow discovery conventions (e.g., links must be <code>&lt;a href&gt;</code> or <code>a[route\:link]</code>)</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Example &mdash; rich navigation with icons and badges:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;nav aria-label="Main" nav:list&gt;
  &lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
      &lt;a route:link="/"&gt;
        &lt;svg class="nav-icon"&gt;&lt;!-- dashboard icon --&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;
        Dashboard
        &lt;span class="badge"&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
      &lt;a route:link="/settings"&gt;
        &lt;svg class="nav-icon"&gt;&lt;!-- gear icon --&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;
        Settings
      &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/nav&gt;</code></pre>

<p><code>NavListBehavior</code> discovers <code>a[href]</code> elements and manages roving tabindex on them. It does not care what's <em>inside</em> the <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> &mdash; icons, badges, status dots, or plain text all work. <strong>This is WE's strongest differentiator.</strong> React headless libraries use hooks + props getters; WE uses behavior attributes &mdash; same separation, but declarative and HTML-first.</p>


<h3>Strategy C: Attribute-Based Configuration</h3>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Details</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td>
      <td>HTML attributes control behavior variants; also serve as CSS selectors</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>WE Status</strong></td>
      <td><strong>Already implemented</strong> &mdash; dominant configuration pattern</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Analogy</strong></td>
      <td>Lit reactive properties, Shoelace attribute API</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>What it solves</strong></td>
      <td>Variant selection visible in HTML, dual-purpose as CSS selectors</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Limitation</strong></td>
      <td>Limited to string values; complex configuration needs parsing or injectors</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Example:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;nav nav:list orientation="horizontal" density="compact"&gt;</code></pre>

<p>CSS targets these directly:</p>
<pre><code>nav[orientation="horizontal"] { flex-direction: row; }
nav[density="compact"] a { padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem; font-size: 0.85rem; }</code></pre>


<h3>Strategy D: CSS Custom Properties as Design Tokens</h3>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Details</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td>
      <td>CSS custom properties define component styling hooks; cascade through the DOM</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Web Standard</strong></td>
      <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Using_CSS_custom_properties">CSS Custom Properties</a> (Baseline), <a href="https://www.designtokens.org/tr/drafts/format/">W3C Design Tokens Format 2025.10</a></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>What it solves</strong></td>
      <td>Theming, visual variation without structural changes; pierces Shadow DOM</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Limitation</strong></td>
      <td>Only controls CSS values; cannot inject structure or behavior</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Three-tier token architecture:</p>
<pre><code>/* Tier 1: Global primitives */
:root { --color-indigo-600: #4f46e5; }

/* Tier 2: Semantic mappings */
:root { --color-interactive: var(--color-indigo-600); }

/* Tier 3: Component-specific */
nav[nav\:list] {
  --nav-active-color: var(--color-interactive);
  --nav-active-bg: color-mix(in srgb, var(--nav-active-color), transparent 90%);
  --nav-icon-size: 1.25rem;
  --nav-badge-bg: var(--color-danger, #ef4444);
}

/* Compact variant overrides tokens */
nav[density="compact"] {
  --nav-icon-size: 1rem;
  --nav-item-padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem;
}</code></pre>


<h3>Strategy E: Injector-Based Context Configuration</h3>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Details</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td>
      <td>Ancestor elements provide configuration through the injector chain; descendants look it up</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>WE Status</strong></td>
      <td><strong>Already implemented</strong> &mdash; InjectorRoot, CustomContext</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Analogy</strong></td>
      <td>React Context, Vue provide/inject, Angular DI</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>What it solves</strong></td>
      <td>Same component behaves differently in different apps or subtrees; no prop drilling</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Limitation</strong></td>
      <td>Requires a DOM node in the ancestor chain to host the injector</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Example &mdash; different nav configuration per application:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;!-- App A provides minimal nav config --&gt;
&lt;div data-inject="navConfig: { icons: false, badges: false }"&gt;
  &lt;nav nav:list&gt;...&lt;/nav&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- App B provides rich nav config --&gt;
&lt;div data-inject="navConfig: { icons: true, badges: true }"&gt;
  &lt;nav nav:list&gt;...&lt;/nav&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

<p>The same <code>nav:list</code> behavior resolves configuration from its injector chain. Different ancestor providers produce different behavior &mdash; no component API changes needed.</p>


<h3>Strategy F: Named Slots (Shadow DOM)</h3>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Details</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td>
      <td>Shadow DOM <code>&lt;slot name="..."&gt;</code> defines injection points; consumer projects content into named positions</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Web Standard</strong></td>
      <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Web_components/Using_templates_and_slots">HTML Slot</a> (Baseline), <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/::slotted">::slotted()</a>, <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/::part">::part()</a></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>What it solves</strong></td>
      <td>Structured content injection at specific positions (icon, label, badge, suffix) with fallback content</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Limitation</strong></td>
      <td>Requires Shadow DOM; <code>::slotted()</code> only matches top-level projected nodes; styling boundary</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Example &mdash; a nav-item Custom Element with named slots:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;!-- Shadow DOM template --&gt;
&lt;a part="link"&gt;
  &lt;slot name="icon"&gt;&lt;/slot&gt;
  &lt;slot&gt;&lt;!-- default: label text --&gt;&lt;/slot&gt;
  &lt;slot name="badge"&gt;&lt;/slot&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;!-- Consumer usage --&gt;
&lt;nav-item href="/inbox"&gt;
  &lt;svg slot="icon"&gt;...&lt;/svg&gt;
  Inbox
  &lt;span slot="badge"&gt;12&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/nav-item&gt;</code></pre>

<p><strong>Tension with WE:</strong> WE currently uses light DOM behaviors (CustomAttribute), not Shadow DOM components. The light DOM approach keeps things simple, styleable, and progressive-enhancement-friendly. Slots require Shadow DOM.</p>

<p><strong>Selective Shadow DOM approach:</strong> Use Shadow DOM only for components that genuinely need structured content projection. The nav <em>item</em> could be a Custom Element with Shadow DOM, while <code>NavListBehavior</code> stays as a light DOM behavior on the parent <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>. The behavior discovers <code>&lt;nav-item&gt;</code> elements just as it discovers <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> elements today.</p>


<h3>Strategy G: CSS <code>::part()</code> for Styling Hooks</h3>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Details</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td>
      <td>Components expose internal elements via <code>part</code> attribute; consumers style with <code>::part(name)</code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Web Standard</strong></td>
      <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/::part">::part()</a> (Baseline)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>What it solves</strong></td>
      <td>Visual variation of Shadow DOM components without structural changes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Limitation</strong></td>
      <td>Only visible to direct parent (no deep ancestor); requires Shadow DOM</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Example:</p>
<pre><code>/* Consumer styles a nav-item's internal parts */
nav-item::part(link) { text-decoration: none; }
nav-item::part(icon) { color: var(--nav-icon-color); }
nav-item::part(badge) { background: var(--nav-badge-bg); border-radius: 9999px; }</code></pre>


<h3>Strategy H: Custom States via <code>CustomStateSet</code></h3>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Details</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td>
      <td>Custom elements expose boolean states via <code>ElementInternals.states</code>; CSS targets with <code>:state(name)</code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Web Standard</strong></td>
      <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CustomStateSet">CustomStateSet</a> (Chrome 125+, Safari 17.4+)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>What it solves</strong></td>
      <td>CSS can target dynamic component states without data attributes or class names</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Limitation</strong></td>
      <td>Custom Elements only (not CustomAttribute); Firefox support still maturing</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Example:</p>
<pre><code>// Inside a Custom Element
this.#internals.states.add('has-badge');
this.#internals.states.add('expanded');

/* CSS targeting custom states */
nav-item:state(has-badge)::part(badge) { display: inline-flex; }
nav-section:state(expanded) { --chevron-rotation: 180deg; }</code></pre>


<h3>Strategy I: Emerging Platform APIs</h3>

