<h2>The WE Configuration Stack</h2>

<p>Rather than picking one strategy, these compose into layers that play to WE's existing strengths:</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Layer</th>
      <th>Mechanism</th>
      <th>What It Configures</th>
      <th>WE Status</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Behavior</strong></td>
      <td>CustomAttribute composition (Strategy A)</td>
      <td>What the component <em>does</em></td>
      <td>Core pattern</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Structure</strong></td>
      <td>Consumer-owned markup / headless behaviors (Strategy B)</td>
      <td>What the component <em>contains</em></td>
      <td>Already implemented</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Variant</strong></td>
      <td>HTML attributes as selectors (Strategy C)</td>
      <td>Which variant is <em>active</em></td>
      <td>Already implemented</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Appearance</strong></td>
      <td>CSS custom properties + @layer (Strategy D)</td>
      <td>How the component <em>looks</em></td>
      <td>Available, not yet standardized</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Context</strong></td>
      <td>Injector-provided configuration (Strategy E)</td>
      <td>How the component <em>varies by app</em></td>
      <td>Already implemented</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Projection</strong></td>
      <td>Named slots / selective Shadow DOM (Strategy F)</td>
      <td>Where custom content <em>goes</em></td>
      <td>Not yet adopted</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p><strong>Key finding:</strong> WE behaviors are <em>already headless by nature</em>. They attach to arbitrary elements and manage state/accessibility without dictating structure. This means the consumer always controls the markup &mdash; icons, badges, popovers, or any other content can be added directly in the HTML. The behavior layer neither adds nor constrains visual content.</p>


<h2>The Primary Gap: Structured Content Projection</h2>

<p>The configuration stack above handles most customization scenarios. The one significant gap is <strong>structured content injection into specific positions</strong> &mdash; a defined API for "put your icon here, your badge there."</p>

<p>Currently, WE solves this implicitly: the consumer writes the markup, and the behavior discovers items regardless of their internal structure. This works well but lacks the <em>explicit contract</em> of named slots. Consumers must read documentation to know where to put things.</p>

<h3>Three Approaches to Fill the Gap</h3>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Approach</th>
      <th>Mechanism</th>
      <th>Trade-offs</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Convention-based discovery</strong></td>
      <td>Behaviors look for elements with specific attributes or roles within their scope (e.g., <code>[slot="icon"]</code>, <code>[data-nav-badge]</code>)</td>
      <td>Simplest; most HTML-native; no Shadow DOM needed; but no enforced contract</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Selective Shadow DOM</strong></td>
      <td>Use Shadow DOM (with <code>&lt;slot&gt;</code>) only for components that need structured projection; behaviors stay in light DOM</td>
      <td>Cleaner API; true encapsulation; but introduces Shadow DOM styling boundary</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Template stamping</strong></td>
      <td>Consumer provides <code>&lt;template&gt;</code> elements for each section; behavior stamps them into position</td>
      <td>Flexible; no Shadow DOM; but more verbose for simple cases</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>


<h2>Headless UI: WE's Natural Position</h2>

<p>The headless component movement (Radix, Ark UI, Downshift, React Aria) emerged because React's component model couples behavior and rendering. These libraries extract behavior into hooks or state machines, returning props for the consumer to spread onto their own elements.</p>

<p>WE does not have this coupling problem. Behaviors (CustomAttribute) never owned the rendering in the first place. The HTML <em>is</em> the rendering layer, and behaviors are pure orchestrators. This means:</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Headless Pattern</th>
      <th>React Approach</th>
      <th>WE Equivalent</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Props getters</td>
      <td><code>getItemProps()</code> spreads ARIA + handlers</td>
      <td>Behavior auto-sets ARIA + tabindex on discovered elements</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Compound components</td>
      <td><code>Menu.Root</code> / <code>Menu.Item</code> share Context</td>
      <td>Parent behavior discovers child elements; injector shares state</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>State machines (Zag.js)</td>
      <td>Machine drives behavior; view is adapter</td>
      <td>Behavior drives state; HTML is the "adapter"</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Unstyled primitives</td>
      <td>Component renders unstyled; consumer adds classes</td>
      <td>No component rendering &mdash; consumer writes <em>all</em> HTML</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p><strong>WE is more headless than headless libraries.</strong> Headless UI libraries still render DOM (a <code>&lt;div role="menu"&gt;</code>, etc). WE behaviors render nothing &mdash; they enhance whatever DOM the consumer provides.</p>


<h2>Recommendations (Ranked)</h2>

<h3>Tier 1: Already Validated &mdash; Formalize and Document</h3>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Consumer-owned markup (headless behaviors)</strong> as the primary configuration story. Document the "discovery contract" for each behavior &mdash; what elements it looks for, what attributes it manages.</li>
  <li><strong>Attribute-based variants</strong> with CSS selector conventions. Establish a standard set of configuration attributes: <code>orientation</code>, <code>density</code>, <code>variant</code>, <code>size</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Injector-based context</strong> for app-level configuration. Document how to provide and consume configuration through the injector chain.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Tier 2: High-Value Additions</h3>
<ol start="4">
  <li><strong>CSS custom property conventions</strong> &mdash; Define a three-tier token architecture (primitives, semantic, component-specific) and a naming convention. Publish token documentation per block.</li>
  <li><strong>Convention-based content discovery</strong> &mdash; Behaviors look for <code>[slot="icon"]</code>, <code>[slot="badge"]</code> etc. in light DOM. No Shadow DOM needed, but provides a documented injection contract.</li>
  <li><strong>Popover API + Invoker Commands integration</strong> &mdash; Many "injected content" scenarios (tooltips, menus, context panels) are now solved natively. Build behaviors that leverage <code>popover</code>, <code>commandfor</code>, and CSS Anchor Positioning.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Tier 3: Worth Exploring</h3>
<ol start="7">
  <li><strong>Selective Shadow DOM</strong> for high-projection components &mdash; If certain blocks (droplist, data table cells) need true slot-based projection, adopt Shadow DOM for those while keeping behaviors in light DOM.</li>
  <li><strong>CustomStateSet for behavior-driven states</strong> &mdash; When WE behaviors are attached to Custom Elements, they could set custom states via <code>ElementInternals</code>, enabling <code>:state(expanded)</code> CSS selectors.</li>
  <li><strong>Declarative Shadow DOM for SSR</strong> &mdash; When SSR support becomes a priority, Declarative Shadow DOM allows server-rendered components with pre-filled slots.</li>
</ol>


<h2>Open Questions</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Should WE define a "slot" convention in light DOM?</strong> Using <code>[slot="icon"]</code> attributes without Shadow DOM gives a familiar API but conflates with the native <code>slot</code> attribute. Should WE use <code>[data-slot="icon"]</code> or a custom attribute name instead?</li>
  <li><strong>Should token naming be standardized per block?</strong> If each block publishes its CSS custom properties (e.g., <code>--nav-*</code>, <code>--tab-*</code>), should there be a formal registry or just documentation?</li>
  <li><strong>When should a block "upgrade" to Shadow DOM?</strong> What criteria determine when light DOM headless behaviors hit their limit and a Shadow DOM component is warranted?</li>
  <li><strong>How should behaviors compose with Custom Elements?</strong> Today behaviors target any element. If some elements become Custom Elements (with Shadow DOM), how do behaviors discover and manage items inside the Shadow DOM? Should <code>nav:list</code> walk into shadow roots?</li>
  <li><strong>Should WE adopt Zag-style state machines?</strong> Encoding behavior as framework-agnostic state machines would make blocks portable beyond WE. Is this worth the complexity for an HTML-first library?</li>
</ol>
